ry of the Holy Grail and The Story of Merlin and concluded by The Quest for the Holy Grail and The Death of Arthur. This volume brings together thirteen essays by noted scholars from the first symposium ever devoted exclusively to the Lancelot-Grail Cycle. Exploring the cycle's evolution across the literatures of medieval France, Italy, Spain, Catalonia, and England, the authors take a variety of approaches that highlight a broad range of cultural, social, historical, and political concerns and offer a comparative and interdisciplinary vision of this great romance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBaumgartner, Emmanuele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, E. Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Carleton W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChase, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, E. Kay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Elspeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKibler, William W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKibler, William W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLacy, Norris F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazzocco, Elizabeth H. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickens, Rupert T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharrer, Harvey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuard, Franrois, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators